      <hedline>
        <hl1>World Without Privacy; Fighting Cyberhate</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Wilson Lee letter says that although the Internet makes it easier to spread messages of hate, it also should enable groups like the Anti-Defamation League to promote their own messages of tolerance; opposes censorship of Internet (July 3 Abraham H Foxman letter)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Abraham H. Foxman of the Anti-Defamation League suggests (letter, July 3) that something must be done about hate sites on the Internet. Surely he is not suggesting some form of censorship as a solution? The Supreme Court, in its decision striking down the Communications Decency Act last year, held that the Internet deserved more free-speech protection than other broadcast media.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Abraham H. Foxman of the Anti-Defamation League suggests (letter, July 3) that something must be done about hate sites on the Internet. Surely he is not suggesting some form of censorship as a solution? The Supreme Court, in its decision striking down the Communications Decency Act last year, held that the Internet deserved more free-speech protection than other broadcast media.</p>
        <p>Mr. Foxman correctly says that the Internet will make it easier to spread messages of hate. That is the price we must pay for the First Amendment. But the Internet should also enable groups like the Anti-Defamation League to promote their own messages of tolerance in opposition to the hatemongers. I hope that is what Mr. Foxman had in mind.</p>
        <p>WILSON LEE  San Diego, July 3, 1998</p>
      </block>
